Welcome to Amazon Sumerian! In this tutorial we will cover many of the Sumerian basics. The end result will be a furnished room with a light switch. A user can click on the Light switch to make it flip up and down and to turn on/off a light. Note: This tutorial uses HTML3D is not currently supported in Virtual Reality. Therefore, the results of this exercise will not be fully supported in VR. In this exercise, we will learn and accomplish the following:

Create a room with primitive entities (Box)
Cover lighting basics
Import entities from the asset library
Place and move objects
Create interactive behaviors using the State Machine
Add basic animations


This is the scene we will build in this tutorial (Note: Using Sumerian Hosts will not be covered in this exercise). Be sure you are using the latest version of your browser.
Prerequisites
Before you begin, you should have completed the following tasks and tutorials:

Sign in to Amazon Sumerian with your AWS account
Complete the Introduction to the Amazon Sumerian Interface tutorial.

Getting Started: Creating a New Scene
From the AWS console, find Amazon Sumerian or go directly to the Dashboard. From the dashboard, create a new Empty scene.

Step 1: Add a Box and Lights
In this step, we will add a simple Box and 3 lights (Point, Directional, Spot). We will then move and reposition the Light entities.


Click Create Entity above the canvas, and select a Box to add to your scene.



Next, we will add 3 lights by clicking Create Entity. Under the Lights category letâs start by adding a Point light.


The Transform component defines an entityâs position in 3D space. We want to adjust the Transform values so they are above and shining down on the box. You can change Transform values by clicking and dragging the handles attached to the entity (i.e. colored arrows) or by manually changing the numerical values in the component.



Repeat this process for the Directional and Spot lights.


Rename the Light entities by selecting each Light in the Entities panel, and then selecting the top component in the Inspector panel on the right. You will see a Name text box.



Rename each light according to itâs light type: Point, Directional, and Spot.

Note: The Lightsâ Transform values will not affect the outcome of this exercise. Move them to wherever you like.
We will position our lights with the following Transform values:
Point:

Directional:

Spot:

Note on Lights: For Directional lights, Translation values (that is the positional coordinates within our scene) do not affect how a light is cast onto objects within a scene, while Rotation values do affect the light cast. Conversely, for the Point light, Rotation values do not affect the light cast while Translation values do affect the light cast. The Spot light is affected by both Rotation and Translation.


To change the Rotation of the Directional and Spot lights, change or the Rotation values in the Transform component, or click the Rotation handles button. This will provide your entities with rings that you can then click and drag to change the rotation. Rotate your lights so they are pointing at the Box.



Finally, we want to group all three of our Light entities into a single parent entity. From the Create Entity menu, add an Empty entity.



Rename the empty entity to âLightsâ.


In the Entities, panel drag and drop each light entity onto your new empty Lights entity (this will group all three light entities as children of the parent Lights entity).



Step 2: Creating a Room Using a Primitive Box
In this step, we will create a room by using a Box. We will change the Transform values and changing the Culling so we will only see the inside of the Box (by only rendering the inner faces of the Box).


Create a Box entity and rename it âRoomâ.


With the Room entity selected, expand the Material component and then open the Culling property.


Change the Cull Face drop down option to Front.

Note: This makes it so we will only see the inside of the Box by only rendering the inner faces of the Room.


Change the Transform values to the following. Note: We do recommend making your Room Transform values identical to ours!



Optional: Change the color of the room by expanding the Material component, and then open the Color (Diffuse) property. Change the color using the color picker. We will choose a pink color.



Step 3: Importing Objects (furniture)
In this step, we will import several objects to furnish our room. We will add a chair, table, rug, and lamp. Feel free to import any objects you like.


Click Import Assets above the canvas. This will open the asset library.



Scroll down to find the furniture assets. We will select and add a chair.



Once the object/asset populates in the Asset Panel expand the asset pack contents and find the entity asset type, which has a hexagon icon next to it. Drag the entity onto the canvas.



Rename your entity to âChairâ.  Note: You can rename the entity âChairâ either from the Asset Panel or the Entities panel.


Position your Chair somewhere in your room by changing the Transform values.



To practice adding more objects to your scene, try adding the following:

Table
Lamp
Rug

Your scene should look something like this:

Step 4: Customizing Textures
In this step, we will place a custom picture on the wall by using a Quad entity and then adding a custom image as the texture.


From the Create Entity menu, add a Quad.



Rename the Quad âPictureâ.


Position the Picture somewhere on the wall and adjust the Scale values to be (1, 1.5. 1).



With the Picture entity selected, expand the Material component and then expand the Color (Diffuse) property. Either upload your own image or drag and drop your own image on the texture drop input. We will use a picture taken in Seattle.



Our scene will look something like the following:

Step 5: Adding a Light Switch
In this step, we will add the Light switch.


Open the asset library. Search for and add the Light switch asset.



Like you did with the furniture entities, from the Assets panel, add the Light Switch entity to your scene.


The light switch will appear in your scene but it will probably be too small to see. Change the Scale of the light switch to (7, 7, 7). Move the Light switch to be somewhere on the wall:



Lastly, we want to move the switch to be in the down position (not sticking straight out like it is currently). In the Entities panel, expand the light switch entity until you can see the light_switch child entity. Select it.



Adjust the Z Rotation of the light_switch entity to 23.



Adjust Your Lights
In this step, we will move the Point light to sit inside the lightbulb of the Lamp entity.


Use the Translation handles to move your Point light to be inside the Lamp.



Now that we have everything in our scene, we can adjust the lights. Rotate the Directional and Spot lights to a position of your liking.



Step 6: State Machine Behaviors
A State Machine is the system to build behaviors, which are changes to entities initiated by a user. Behaviors can act alone or they can act in a sequence. They can
be movements, animations, sounds, camera changes, collisions, reactions, AWS service integrations, etc. Behaviors are built using a collection of States that are connected by Transitions, as an entity transitions from one state to another.
In this step, we will create 2 behaviors that will each serve a different purpose. The Switch On/Off behavior will allow a user to click the light switch so that it flips up and down (technically, it will be rotating). This behavior will also emit a message that can be used by our second behavior (Light On/Off) to initiate, thus turning the lights on and off.
Switch On/Off Behavior
This behavior will be attached to the light_switch object inside the Light switch entity (i.e. the switch of the light switch).


Select the light_switch entity, nested under the light switch.


In the Inspector panel, click Add Component and add a State Machine component.



Click the + button to add a new behavior. This will open the State Machine editor.


Rename the behavior âSwitch On/Off Behaviorâ.



With the default, and only, State 1 selected, change the name of the state to âWait for Clickâ and then click Add Action.



This will open the action library. Search for and add the Click/Tap on entity action.



Add a new state.



Change the name to âFlip Upâ.


Add another action. Search for and add the Tween Rotate action.


Adjust the actionâs properties to the following:



Add another state. Rename the new state âEmit Onâ.


Add another action. Search for and add the Emit Message action.


In the Channel message, type âlightOnâ (this is case sensitive!).


Add another action. Search for and add the Transition action.



Select the Wait for Click state and duplicate it.



Reposition the states node and then duplicate the Flip Up state. Rename to Flip Down. Change the properties to the following:



Duplicate the Emit On state and rename to âEmit Offâ. Change the Channel message to âlightOffâ.



In the State Graph, reposition the state nodes to the following by clicking and dragging:



Now we need to add transitions between each state. Starting with the first Wait for Click action, click the transition label (i.e. âOn Click/Tap Entity) at the bottom of the state. Drag a transition arrow to the next state.



Do that for all the states until the behavior cycle is completed.

Note: Make sure the first Wait for Click state is set as the Initial State.
Test your behavior! Press play and click on the switch. See it flip up and down. If you have the State Machine editor open, see the states transitioning.
Light On/Off Behavior
Letâs create a behavior for the Point Light. This behavior will turn the light on and off. To have it occur on the click of the light, we will use the messages being emitted by our first behavior (âlightOnâ & âlightOffâ). We will start this new behavior by using a Listen action.


Select Point Light and add a State Machine. Add a new behavior and name it âLight On/Off Behaviorâ.



Change the name of State 1 to âListen for Onâ. Add an action. Search for and add a Listen action. In the Message channel add the âlightOnâ message.



Add another state. Rename it âLight Onâ. Add an action. Search for and add a Set Light Properties action. Make sure the Intensity is set to 1. Add a Transition action. Finally, click this state to be Set As Initial State. This will turn off the lights as soon as the scene begins.



Duplicate the Listen for On state. Rename âListen for Offâ. Change the Message channel to âlightOffâ.



Duplicate the Light On state. Rename âLight Offâ. Change the Intensity to 0. Click Set as Initial State (because we want the light to be off when we start the scene).



Finally, starting with the Light Off state (our initial state), add transitions clockwise. Your behavior should look like this:



Press play and click the Light switch to see your Point Light turn on and off!
Apply Behavior to Other Entities
The Light On/Off Behavior works with the Point Light. In this final step, letâs apply the same behavior to another Light entity.


Select the Directional Light entity.


Add a State Machine component.


In the Assets panel, filter to only see Behaviors.



Drag and drop the Light On/Off Behavior onto the Directional Light drop input in the State Machine component.



Test your scene again to turn on/off both the Point and Directional light.
Now publish and share your scene!
Additional and Optional Steps
Consider the experimenting with following steps:

Adding a Host for Instruction: Add a Host with a custom speech that provides instruction to click the light switch. See the Speech Component tutorial for more information.
Add a Skybox/Skysphere: Import a 360 image skybox from the Import Assets Library, and add it to the Environment component. See the Skybox/Skysphere tutorial for more information.
Play/Stop Sound Upon Click: Add a Sound component to the Room entity and add a song/audio file to your scene. In the Light On/Off Behavior, add Play Sound and Pause Sound actions to play/pause your audio file.

Related Tutorials
Now that you understand more about lights and cameras, you should learn more about light placement and the relationship between lights and materials. See the following:

